# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: automatic-fire-suppression
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/2-2-dichloro-1-1-1-trifluoroethane] Its ozone depletion potential is ODP = 0.012, and global warming potential is GWP = 76.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/2-2-dichloro-1-1-1-trifluoroethane] HCFC-123 will eventually be phased out under the current schedule of the Montreal Protocol.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/2-2-dichloro-1-1-1-trifluoroethane] It was discontinued in new HVAC equipment in 2020 in developed countries but will still be produced for service use of HVAC equipment until 2030.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/2-2-dichloro-1-1-1-trifluoroethane] Developing countries can continue to use It in new equipment until 2030 and will be produced for use in service there until 2040.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/2-2-dichloro-1-1-1-trifluoroethane] HCFC-123 is used in large tonnage centrifugal chiller applications, and is the most efficient refrigerant currently in use in the marketplace for HVAC applications.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/2-2-dichloro-1-1-1-trifluoroethane] HCFC-123 is also used as a testing agent for bypass leakage of carbon adsorbers in gas filtration systems, and as the primary chemical in Halotron I fire-extinguishing agent.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/2-2-dichloro-1-1-1-trifluoroethane] Cylinders of HCFC-123 were a light grey prior to the elimination of cylinder color identification.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/2-2-dichloro-1-1-1-trifluoroethane] 2,2-Dichloro-1,1,1-trifluoroethane can be produced by reacting tetrachloroethylene with hydrogen fluoride in the gas phase.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/2-2-dichloro-1-1-1-trifluoroethane] This reaction can give 1,2-dichloro-1,1,2-trifluoroethane as a byproduct.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/3m] The **3M Company** (originally the **Minnesota Mining and Manufacturing Company**) is an American multinational conglomerate operating in the fields of industry, worker safety, and consumer goods.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/3m] Among its best-known consumer brands are Scotch Tape, Scotchgard surface protectants, Post-it notes, and Nexcare adhesive bandages.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/3m] 3M's stock ticker symbol is MMM and is listed on the New York Stock Exchange, Inc.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/3m] 3M made $35.4 billion in total sales in 2021 and ranked number 102 in the *Fortune* 500 list of the largest United States corporations by total revenue.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/3m] As of 2021, the company had approximately 95,000 employees and operations in more than 70 countries.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/3m] There are a few international subsidiaries, such as 3M India, 3M Japan, and 3M Canada.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/3m] Five businessmen founded the Minnesota Mining and Manufacturing Company as a mining venture in Two Harbors, Minnesota, making their first sale on June 13, 1902.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/3m] The goal was to mine corundum, a crystalline form of aluminium oxide, which failed because the mine's mineral holdings were anorthosite, a feldspar which had no commercial value.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/3m] Co-founder John Dwan solicited funds in exchange for stock and Edgar Ober and Lucius Ordway took over the company in 1905.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/3m] The company moved to Duluth and began researching and producing sandpaper products.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/3m] McKnight, later a key executive, joined the company in 1907, and A.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/3m] 3M finally became financially stable in 1916 and was able to pay dividends.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/3m] The company moved to Saint Paul in 1910, where it remained for 52 years before outgrowing the campus and moving to its current headquarters at 3M Center in Maplewood, Minnesota, in 1962.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/3m] In 1947, 3M began producing perfluorooctanoic acid (PFOA), an industrial surfactant and chemical feedstock, by electrochemical fluorination.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/3m] In 1951, DuPont purchased PFOA from then-Minnesota Mining and Manufacturing Company for use in the manufacturing of teflon, a product that brought DuPont a billion-dollar-a-year profit by the 1990s.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/3m] The original formula for Scotchgard, a water repellent applied to fabrics, was discovered accidentally in 1952 by 3M chemists Patsy Sherman and Samuel Smith.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/3m] Sales began in 1956, and in 1973 the two chemists received a patent for the formula.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/3m] In the late 1950s, 3M produced the first asthma inhaler, but the company did not enter the pharmaceutical industry until the mid-1960s with the acquisition of Riker Laboratories, moving it from California to Minnesota.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/3m] 3M retained the Riker Laboratories name for the subsidiary until at least 1985.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/3m] In the mid-1990s, 3M Pharmaceuticals, as the division came to be called, produced the first CFC-free asthma inhaler in response to adoption of the Montreal Protocol by the United States.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/3m] In the 1980s and 1990s, the company spent fifteen years developing a topical cream delivery technology which led in 1997 to health authority approval and marketing of a symptomatic treatment for genital warts, Aldara.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/3m] 3M divested its pharmaceutical unit through three deals in 2006, netting more than US$2 billion.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/3m] At the time, 3M Pharmaceuticals comprised about 20% of 3M's healthcare business and employed just over a thousand people.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/3m] By the 1970s, 3M developed a theatrical blood formula based on red colorfast microbeads suspended in a carrier liquid.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/3m] This stage blood was sold as Nextel Simulated Blood and was used during the production of the 1978 film *Dawn of the Dead*.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/3m] In the late 1970s, 3M Mincom was involved in some of the first digital audio recordings to see commercial release when a prototype machine was brought to the Sound 80 studios in Minneapolis.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/3m] In 1979 3M introduced a digital audio recording system called "3M Digital Audio Mastering System".
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/3m] 3M launched "Press 'n Peel", a sticky bookmark page holder in stores in four cities in 1977, but the results were disappointing.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/3m] A year later 3M instead issued free samples of the product as a sticky note directly to consumers in Boise, Idaho, with 95% of those who tried them indicating they would buy it.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/3m] The product was introduced as "Post-Its" in 1979, and was sold across the United States from April 6, 1980.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/3m] The following year they were launched in Canada and Europe.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/3m] In 1980, the company acquired Comtal, a manufacturer of digital image processors.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/3m] In 1996, the company's data storage and imaging divisions were spun off as Imation Corporation.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/3m] In doing so, 3M shed 20% of its sales, employees and product lines at a cost of only 5% of its profits and immediately looked much improved in the estimation of Wall Street analysts.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/3m] These businesses, with annual sales of over $2 billion, had generated handsome profits for 3M which funded the research and development of many new product lines, but these were largely in "sunset" industries: printing products, photographic film, and removable storage media.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/3m] Imation shortly sold its imaging and photographic film businesses largely to Kodak in order to concentrate on storage.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/3m] Imation was purchased by a hedge fund in 2016 and ceased to exist as an independent business.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/3m] Its successor is now called Glassbridge Enterprises, an American holding company.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/3m] On April 8, 2002, 3M's 100th anniversary, the company changed its legal name to "3M Company".
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/3m] On September 8, 2008, 3M announced an agreement to acquire Meguiar's, a car-care products company that was family-owned for over a century.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/3m] In August 2010, 3M acquired Cogent Systems for $943 million, and on October 13, 2010, 3M completed acquisition of Arizant Inc.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/3m] In December 2011, 3M completed the acquisition of the Winterthur Technology Group, a bonded abrasives company.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/3m] In 2011, 3M created CloudLibrary as part of its library systems unit as a competitor to OverDrive, Inc.; in 2015 3M sold the North American part of that unit to Bibliotheca Group GmbH, a company founded in 2011 that was funded by One Equity Partners Capital Advisors, a division of JP Morgan Chase.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/3m] As of 2012, 3M was one of the 30 companies included in the Dow Jones Industrial Average, added on August 9, 1976, and was 97 on the 2011 Fortune 500 list.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/3m] On January 3, 2012, it was announced that the Office and Consumer Products Division of Avery Dennison was being bought by 3M for $550 million.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/3m] The transaction was canceled by 3M in September 2012 amid antitrust concerns.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/3m] In May 2013, 3M sold Scientific Anglers and Ross Reels to Orvis.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/3m] Ross Reels had been acquired by 3M in 2010.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/3m] In March 2017, 3M purchased Johnson Controls International Plc's safety gear business, Scott Safety, for $2 billion.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/3m] In 2017, 3M had net sales for the year of $31.657 billion, up from $30.109 billion the year before.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/3m] In 2018, it was reported that the company would pay $850 million to end the Minnesota water pollution case concerning perfluorochemicals.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/3m] Roman was appointed CEO by the board of directors.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/3m] On December 19, 2018, 3M announced it had entered into a definitive agreement to acquire the technology business of M*Modal, for a total enterprise value of $1.0 billion.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/3m] In October 2019, 3M purchased Acelity and its KCI subsidiaries for $6.7 billion, including assumption of debt and other adjustments.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/3m] On May 1, 2020, 3M divested substantially all of its drug delivery business to an affiliate of Altaris Capital Partners, LLC. for approximately $650 million, including a 17% interest in the new operating company, Kindeva Drug Delivery.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/3m] In December 2021, 3M announced that it would merge its food-safety business with food testing and animal healthcare products maker Neogen.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/3m] The deal, with an enterprise value of about $5.3 billion, closed in September 2022.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/3m] In July 2022, the company announced it would spin off its healthcare assets to form a new, independent firm, likely completing the transaction in 2023.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/3m] 3M will retain an ownership stake of 19.9% in the new, publicly traded health care company and gradually divest the holdings.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/3m] The company will be known as Solventum Corporation.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/3m] In December 2022, the company announced plans to stop producing and using so-called forever chemicals (per and polyfluoroalkyl), which have been commonly used in items such as food packaging, cellphones, nonstick pans, firefighting foams, and clothing.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/3m] These chemicals are well known for their water-resistant and nonstick properties, but they are also dangerous pollutants that are linked to serious health problems, including ulcerative colitis and cancer.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/3m] The move comes as governments in the Netherlands and the United States consider actions against 3M.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/3m] In March 2024, 3M announced the appointment of William "Bill" Brown as chief executive officer to take effect on May 1, 2024.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/3m] Michael Roman would remain in the role of executive chairman.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/3m] Brown, 61, is the former chairman of the board and chief executive officer of L3Harris Technologies.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/3m] As of 2019, 3M produces approximately 60,000 products, and has four business groups focused on safety and industrial, transportation and electronics, health care, and consumer products.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/3m] 3M obtained its first patent in 1924 and acquires approximately 3,000 new patents annually.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/3m] The company surpassed the 100,000-patent threshold in 2014.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/3m] 3M's Pollution Prevention Pays (3P) program was established in 1975.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/3m] The program initially focused on pollution reduction at the plant level and was expanded to promote recycling and reduce waste across all divisions in 1989.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/3m] By the early 1990s, approximately 2,500 3P projects decreased the company's total global pollutant generation by 50 percent and saved 3M $500–600 million by eliminating the production of waste requiring subsequent treatment.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/3m] In 1983, the Oakdale Dump in Oakdale, Minnesota, was listed as an EPA Superfund site after significant groundwater and soil contamination by VOCs and heavy metals was uncovered.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/3m] The Oakdale Dump was a 3M dumping site utilized through the 1940s and 1950s.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/3m] During the 1990s and 2000s, 3M reduced releases of toxic pollutants by 99 percent and greenhouse gas emissions by 72 percent.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/3m] As of 2012, the United States Environmental Protection Agency (EPA) had awarded 3M with the Energy Star Award each year that it has been presented.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/3m] In 1999, the EPA began investigating perfluorinated chemicals after receiving data on the global distribution and toxicity of perfluorooctanesulfonic acid (PFOS).
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/3m] These materials are part of a broad group of perfluoroalkyl and polyfluoroalkyl substances often referred to as PFAS, each of which has different chemical properties.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/3m] 3M, the former primary producer of PFOS from the U.S., announced the phase-out of PFOS, perfluorooctanoic acid, and PFOS-related product production in May 2000.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/3m] Perfluorinated compounds produced by 3M have been used in non-stick cookware, stain-resistant fabrics, and other products.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/3m] The Cottage Grove facility manufactured PFAS from the 1940s to 2002.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/3m] In response to PFAS contamination of the Mississippi River and surrounding area, 3M stated the area will be "cleaned through a combination of groundwater pump-out wells and soil sediment excavation".
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/3m] The restoration plan was based on an analysis of the company property and surrounding lands.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/3m] The on-site water treatment facility that handled the plant's post-production water was not capable of removing PFAS, which were released into the nearby Mississippi River.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/3m] The clean-up cost estimate, which included a granular activated carbon system to remove PFAS from the ground water was $50 to $56 million, funded from a $147 million environmental reserve set aside in 2006.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/3m] In 2008, 3M created the Renewable Energy Division within 3M's Industrial and Transportation Business to focus on Energy Generation and Energy Management.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/3m] In late 2010, the state of Minnesota sued 3M for $5 billion in punitive damages, claiming they released PFCs—classified a toxic chemical by the EPA—into local waterways.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/3m] A settlement for $850 million was reached in February 2018.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/3m] In 2019, 3M, along with the Chemours Company and DuPont, appeared before lawmakers to deny responsibility, with company Senior VP of Corporate Affairs Denise Rutherford arguing that the chemicals pose no human health threats at current levels and that there were no victims.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/3m] In 2021, research had determined that 3M's Zwijndrecht (Belgium) factory caused PFOS pollution that may be contaminating agricultural products within a 15 kilometer radius of the plant which includes Antwerp.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/3m] The Flemish Government has paid 63 million euros for cleanup costs so far with 3M contributing 75,000 euros.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/3m] The Flemish Government issued measures advising against the consumption of, for example, home-grown eggs within a radius of 5 kilometers.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/3m] In 2023, 3M reached an agreement to pay a $10.3bn settlement with numerous US public water systems to resolve thousands of lawsuits over PFAS contamination.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/3m] In May 2026, the Australian government launched legal action against 3M, alleging that the company made false statements regarding the long-term environmental impacts of firefighting foam containing PFAS.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/3m] The government is seeking more than A$2 billion in damages to recover costs incurred in investigating and managing contamination resulting from the use of the foam.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/3m] The government described the lawsuit as the largest legal claim ever brought by Australia.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/3m] Assistant Defence Minister Peter Khalil stated that 28 defence sites across Australia had been impacted by PFAS contamination.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/3m] 3M reported total CO2e emissions (direct and indirect) for the twelve months ending December 31, 2020, at 5,280 Kt (-550 /-9.4% y-o-y) and plans to reduce emissions by 50% by 2030 compared to 2019.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/3m] The company also aims to achieve carbon neutrality by 2050.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/3m] The Combat Arms Earplugs, Version 2 (CAEv2), was developed by Aearo Technologies for U.S. military and civilian use.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/3m] The CAEv2 was a double ended earplug that 3M claimed would offer users different levels of protection.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/3m] Between 2003 and 2015, these earplugs were standard issue to members of the U.S. military.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/3m] In May 2016, Moldex-Metric, Inc., a 3M competitor, filed a whistleblower complaint against 3M under the False Claims Act.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/3m] Moldex-Metric claimed that 3M made false claims to the U.S. government about the safety of its earplugs and that it knew the earplugs had an inherently defective design.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/3m] In 2018, 3M agreed to pay $9.1 million to the U.S. government to resolve the allegations, without admitting liability.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/3m] Since 2018, more than 140,000 former users of the earplugs (primarily U.S. military veterans) have filed suit against 3M claiming they suffer from hearing loss, tinnitus, and other damage as a consequence of the defective design.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/3m] Internal emails showed that 3M officials boasted about charging $7.63 per piece for the earplugs which cost 85 cents to produce.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/3m] The company's official response indicated that the cost to the government includes R&D costs.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/3m] 3M settled close to 260,000 lawsuits in August 2023 by agreeing to pay $6 billion to current and former U.S. military members who were affected.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/3m] The N95 respirator mask was developed by 3M and approved in 1972.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/3m] Due to its ability to filter viral particulates, its use was recommended during the COVID-19 pandemic but supply soon became short.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/3m] Much of the company's supply had already been sold prior to the outbreak.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/3m] The shortages led to the U.S. government asking 3M to stop exporting US-made N95 respirator masks to Canada and to Latin American countries, and President Donald Trump invoked the Defense Production Act to require 3M to prioritize orders from the federal government.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/3m] The dispute was resolved when 3M agreed to import more respirators, mostly from its factories in China.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/3m] 3M later struck a CA$70M deal with the federal government of Canada and the Ontario provincial government to produce N95 masks at their plant in Brockville, Ontario.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/3m] 3M's general offices, corporate research laboratories, and some division laboratories in the U.S. are in St.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/3m] In the United States, 3M operates 80 manufacturing facilities in 29 states, and 125 manufacturing and converting facilities in 37 countries outside the U.S.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/3m] During March 2016, 3M completed a 400,000-square-foot (37,000 m2) research-and-development building on its Maplewood campus that cost $150 million.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/3m] Seven hundred scientists from various divisions occupy the building.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/3m] They were previously scattered across the campus.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/3m] 3M hopes concentrating its research and development in this manner will improve collaboration.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/3m] 3M received $9.6 million in local tax increment financing and relief from state sales taxes in order to assist with development of the building.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/abc-dry-chemical] Dry chemical powder is used on all classes of fires.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/abc-dry-chemical] Dry chemical powder puts out the fire by coating the burning material with a thin layer of dust, thereby separating the fuel from the oxygen in the air.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/abc-dry-chemical] The powder also works to interrupt the chemical reaction of fire, so these extinguishers are extremely effective at putting out the fire.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/abc-dry-chemical] Pressure is generated by gas cartridges stored inside the cylinder.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/abc-dry-chemical] Its force will last for 45 seconds and can reach 3–4.5 metres (10–15 ft).
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/abc-dry-chemical] It insulates Class A fires by melting at approximately 180–200 °C (350–400 °F).
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/abc-dry-chemical] Class A fires are caused by the burning of common combustible materials, such as wood, paper, or most plastics.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/abc-dry-chemical] The powder breaks the chain reaction of liquid and gas fires by coating the surface to which it is applied.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/abc-dry-chemical] These fires (Class B in the US system; Classes B and C in the European and Australian systems) include the burning of gasoline, oil, propane, and natural gas.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/abc-dry-chemical] It is safe and effective for electrical fires since it is a non-conductor of electricity.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/abc-dry-chemical] Fires involving live electrical equipment (Class C in the US system; Class E in the Australian system) need to be put out with equipment that will not conduct its energy back to the user as is the case with water.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/abc-dry-chemical] Electricity can also cause fires of the other classes.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/abc-dry-chemical] Chimney bombs are zip-lock bags or other small bags filled with ABC dry chemical powder.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/abc-dry-chemical] Chimney bombs are used by fire service personnel to help extinguish chimney fires.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/abc-dry-chemical] Creosote, which is the by-product of the incomplete burning of wood (typically due to chronic combustion-air insufficiency), is extinguished by the chain reaction caused by the chimney bombs.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/abc-dry-chemical] Chimney bombs work by first being dropped directly down a chimney, where upon contact with the flue bottom and heat of the fire, they explode, thereby releasing the powder.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/abc-dry-chemical] Then, the natural chimney draft will carry the dry chemical powder up the shaft of the chimney, thus coating the creosote and eventually neutralizing the fire.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/abc-dry-chemical] Use of multiple chimney bombs may be necessary, depending on how severe the fire is.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/abc-dry-chemical] Chimney bombs can also be effective if they are opened and then dropped down the chimney.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/abc-dry-chemical] In order for chimney bombs to be effective, it may be necessary to first unclog the chimney.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/abc-dry-chemical] ABC dry chemical is inappropriate for chlorine or oxidizer fires.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/abc-dry-chemical] The resulting chemical reaction can cause an explosion or a breakdown of the chemicals releasing toxic gases.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/abc-dry-chemical] ABC dry chemical is inappropriate for certain metal fires (Class-D) and does not possess a saponification characteristic and should therefore not be used on Class K / Class F fires.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/abc-dry-chemical] ABC dry chemical has been found to be effective in initially ceasing combustion of oils or fats, however re-application of additional dry chemical may be necessary due to the potential for re-flash of oils or fats heated to near or at their flash point.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/abc-dry-chemical] A Class K / Class F extinguisher is more effective in controlling fires involving primarily vegetable oils as it causes a chemical change to the oils or fats making re-flash far less likely.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/abc-dry-chemical] When a Class K / Class F extinguisher is not available an ABC dry chemical extinguisher can be carefully used to control a fire involving cooking oils or fats if the operator is aware of the potential need to re-apply more chemical if the oils or fats reignite.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/abc-dry-chemical] Due to the corrosive properties of ABC dry chemical, it is not recommended for use around aircraft or sensitive equipment.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/abc-dry-chemical] The powder contains monoammonium phosphate, with the phosphate being a globally valuable material.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/abc-dry-chemical] See the references for links to recycling research projects and companies.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/active-fire-protection] Manual fire suppression includes the use of a fire blanket, fire extinguisher, or a standpipe system.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/active-fire-protection] A fire blanket is a sheet of fire retardant material that is designed to be placed over a fire to smother it out.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/active-fire-protection] Small fire blankets are meant for inception stage fires.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/active-fire-protection] They are normally made of fiberglass or Kevlar.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/active-fire-protection] Larger ones can be found in laboratories and factories, and are designed to be wrapped around a person whose clothes have caught fire.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/active-fire-protection] Fire extinguishers are devices that contain and discharge a substance that extinguishes or puts out a fire.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/active-fire-protection] These handheld devices come in a huge range of sizes, but the most common are portable fire extinguishers, typically weighing up to 15 kg in total.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/active-fire-protection] These can be easily handled and operated by one person and placement can either be wall-mounted, on a fire extinguisher trolley or housed inside a cabinet.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/active-fire-protection] Fire extinguishers are one of the most common manual fire suppression devices and are required in all commercial buildings and vehicles.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/active-fire-protection] Fire extinguishers can be used with little to no training and are meant for small incipient stage fires.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/active-fire-protection] The most common extinguisher is the ABC extinguisher and are found in most offices and homes.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/active-fire-protection] It can be used on normal fires, liquid fires, and electrical fires.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/active-fire-protection] There are also special extinguishers for kitchen fires and for use on burning metals, those being Class K and Class D respectively.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/active-fire-protection] Standpipes are installed in most large, multistory buildings.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/active-fire-protection] There are two types of standpipes: dry and wet.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/active-fire-protection] Most standpipes are dry systems and cannot be used by the public.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/active-fire-protection] Dry systems require a fire engine to pump water into the system.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/active-fire-protection] Most dry systems do not have pre-connected hoses and require firefighters to bring in the hose.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/active-fire-protection] In wet systems, there is always water in the pipes and they can be used by anyone.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/active-fire-protection] Wet systems will have hoses so building occupants can try and extinguish fires.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/active-fire-protection] Wet systems are becoming less common with the increase in number of sprinkler systems being installed.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/active-fire-protection] In some systems, firefighters have the option of pumping a Fire Department Connection (FDC) which will increase the water pressure at a standpipe in the event of a fire pump failure or loss of pressure.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/active-fire-protection] Typically, these systems pressurize the sprinkler system or the standpipe but not both at the same time.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/active-fire-protection] Automatic control means are any form of suppression that requires no human intervention these can include a fire sprinkler system, a gaseous clean agent, or automatic foam suppression system.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/active-fire-protection] Most automatic suppression systems would be found in large commercial kitchens or other high-risk areas.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/active-fire-protection] Fire sprinkler systems are installed in all types of buildings, commercial and residential.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/active-fire-protection] They are usually located at ceiling level and are connected to a reliable water source, most commonly municipal water supply.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/active-fire-protection] A typical automatic sprinkler system operates when heat at the site of a fire causes a fusible link or glass component in the sprinkler head to fail, thereby releasing the water from the sprinkler head.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/active-fire-protection] This means that only the sprinkler heads at the fire location actuate – not all the sprinklers on a floor or in a building.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/active-fire-protection] However, certain systems, such as deluge systems, do spray water from all heads in the same zone upon actuation.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/active-fire-protection] Sprinkler systems help to reduce the growth of a fire, thereby increasing life safety and limiting structural damage.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/active-fire-protection] Gaseous clean agents are installed to result in less fire and water damage than sprinklers, such as in computer rooms.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/active-fire-protection] The system works by flooding an area with a gas which interferes with the fire tetrahedron.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/active-fire-protection] These systems are often found in areas where people are not going to be present when the system is activated such as datacenters, cooling systems, and other industrial applications.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/active-fire-protection] Activating a gaseous clean agent system when people are present can cause injury or death, and are usually equipped with an audible notification system to warn any potential occupants to evacuate the area.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/active-fire-protection] Automatic foam suppression systems come in three main forms low expansion, medium expansion, and high expansion.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/active-fire-protection] Low expansion foam expands less than 20 times its original size.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/active-fire-protection] These systems can be installed in a variety of places but are commonly found in places where hydrocarbons are stored.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/active-fire-protection] Low expansion foam systems when using film forming work by making a blanket of foam over the burning liquid to both cool it down and suppress the vapors.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/active-fire-protection] Medium expansion foam expands between 20 and 200 times its original size.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/active-fire-protection] These can be installed in outdoor settings like transfer stations or for use in open pits.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/active-fire-protection] Medium foam is used outdoors because it is denser than high expansion and will not blow away as easily.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/active-fire-protection] It works by covering what is on fire in a thick blanket of foam to smother it and suppress vapors.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/active-fire-protection] High expansion foam expands between 200 and 1000 times its original size.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/active-fire-protection] These systems are commonly installed in large volume areas like airplane hangars, mine shafts, and ship holds.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/active-fire-protection] These systems are normally installed inside and make a very light foam.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/active-fire-protection] They extinguish the fire by rapid smothering and cooling.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/active-fire-protection] Its rapid rate of expansion enables it to fill large areas with foam rapidly.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/active-fire-protection] When used on LNG tanks they provide an added insulation layer that helps reduce the vapor rate.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/active-fire-protection] Nozzles that are powered by electrical energy that is generated and supplied by fire detection and control devices and are typically closed.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/active-fire-protection] ILDFA uses a dual approach, combining a water-based fire suppression system in conjunction with a hollow, perforated flooring system to drain and remove spilled flammable liquid.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/active-fire-protection] This approach reduces the risk of pool fires inside infrastructure by diverting any leaked fuel away from potential ignition sources or by extinguishing any flammable liquid fire by depriving it of oxygen once it is removed.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/active-fire-protection] Fire detection works using smoke or heat sensors.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/active-fire-protection] These systems are very effective tool at alerting people in the immediate vicinity of where the fire is detected but building regulations require an integrated fire detection system.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/active-fire-protection] These system not only alerts people throughout the building by triggering the fire alarm but it can also summon emergency services.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/active-fire-protection] There are two types of systems available – addressable and conventional.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/active-fire-protection] Addressable systems monitor the specific location of each device (e.g. smoke detector, call point or sounder).
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/active-fire-protection] It means in the event of a fire or other emergency you know exactly where the problem is.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/active-fire-protection] This saves precious time and helps the emergency services prevent the loss of life and serious damage.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/active-fire-protection] Conventional systems can only determine the problem is in a general area and thus are more suited for small sites.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/active-fire-protection] When the fire detection system is activated it can also send an alert to the local fire department, broadcast a prerecorded warning message and unlock the buildings access control system.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/active-fire-protection] Hypoxic air fire prevention systems, also known as oxygen reduction systems are new automatic fire prevention systems that permanently reduce the oxygen concentration inside the protected volumes so that ignition or fire spreading cannot occur.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/active-fire-protection] Unlike traditional fire suppression systems that usually extinguish fire after it is detected, hypoxic air is able to prevent fires.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/active-fire-protection] At lower altitudes hypoxic air is safe to breathe for healthy individuals.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/active-fire-protection] All AFP systems are required to be installed and maintained in accordance with strict guidelines in order to maintain compliance with the local building code and the fire code.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/active-fire-protection] AFP works alongside modern architectural designs and construction materials and fire safety education to prevent, retard, and suppress structural fires.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/area-of-refuge] An **area of refuge** or **safe room** is a place in a building designed to hold occupants during a fire or other emergency when evacuation may not be safe or possible.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/area-of-refuge] Occupants can wait there until rescued or relieved by firefighters.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/area-of-refuge] In some instances, an area of refuge or refuge area may refer to a designated space in a multi-unit residential building that can provide relief from unsafe or uncomfortable conditions in individual units.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/area-of-refuge] An area of refuge is typically supplied with a steady supply of fresh or filtered outside air.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/area-of-refuge] A two way communication system is provided on each floor above or below the main floor.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/area-of-refuge] A call box is required in each area of refuge, which can call into a central location called a base station.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/area-of-refuge] If the station is not attended 24 hours a day, the call must automatically call to an outside location and have two-way voice person to person communication capabilities.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/area-of-refuge] Such locations are usually required to be bounded by fire-resistant walls and floors.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/area-of-refuge] In the context of climate change, where older buildings may not be designed for changing climate conditions, refuge spaces are sometimes discussed in terms of providing communal areas in multi-unit buildings for when temperature and air quality is not safe or comfortable in individual units.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/argon] Nearly all argon in Earth's atmosphere is radiogenic argon-40, derived from the decay of potassium-40 in Earth's crust.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/argon] In the universe, argon-36 is by far the most common argon isotope, as it is the most easily produced by stellar nucleosynthesis in supernovas.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/argon] The name "argon" is derived from the Ancient Greek word ἀργόν, neuter singular form of ἀργός meaning 'lazy' or 'inactive', as a reference to the fact that the element undergoes almost no chemical reactions.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/argon] The complete octet (eight electrons) in the outer atomic shell makes argon stable and resistant to bonding with other elements.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/argon] Its triple point temperature of 83.8058 K is a defining fixed point in the International Temperature Scale of 1990.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/argon] Argon is extracted industrially by the fractional distillation of liquid air.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/argon] It is mostly used as an inert shielding gas in welding and other high-temperature industrial processes where ordinarily unreactive substances become reactive; for example, an argon atmosphere is used in graphite electric furnaces to prevent the graphite from burning.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/argon] It is also used in incandescent and fluorescent lighting, and other gas-discharge tubes.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/argon] It makes a distinctive blue-green gas laser.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/argon] It is also used in fluorescent glow starters.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/argon] Argon has approximately the same solubility in water as oxygen and is 2.5 times more soluble in water than nitrogen.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/argon] Argon is colorless, odorless, nonflammable and nontoxic as a solid, liquid or gas.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/argon] Argon is chemically inert under most conditions and forms no confirmed stable compounds at room temperature.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/argon] Although argon is a noble gas, it can form some compounds under various extreme conditions.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/argon] Argon fluorohydride (HArF), a compound of argon with fluorine and hydrogen that is stable below 17 K (−256.1 °C; −429.1 °F), has been demonstrated.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/argon] Although the neutral ground-state chemical compounds of argon are presently limited to HArF, argon can form clathrates with water when atoms of argon are trapped in a lattice of water molecules.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/argon] Ions, such as ArH+ , and excited-state complexes, such as ArF, have been demonstrated.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/argon] Theoretical calculation predicts several more argon compounds that should be stable but have not yet been synthesized.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/argon] Argon was first isolated from air in 1894 by Lord Rayleigh and Sir William Ramsay at University College London by removing oxygen, carbon dioxide, water, and nitrogen from a sample of clean air.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/argon] They first accomplished this by replicating an experiment of Henry Cavendish's.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/argon] The arc was powered by a battery of five Grove cells and a Ruhmkorff coil of medium size.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/argon] The alkali absorbed the oxides of nitrogen produced by the arc and also carbon dioxide.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/argon] They operated the arc until no more reduction of volume of the gas could be seen for at least an hour or two and the spectral lines of nitrogen disappeared when the gas was examined.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/argon] The remaining oxygen was reacted with alkaline pyrogallate to leave behind an apparently non-reactive gas which they called argon.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/argon] Before isolating the gas, they had determined that nitrogen produced from chemical compounds was 0.5% lighter than nitrogen from the atmosphere.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/argon] The difference was slight, but it was important enough to attract their attention for many months.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/argon] They concluded that there was another gas in the air mixed in with the nitrogen.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/argon] Argon was also encountered in 1882 through independent research of H.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/argon] Each observed new lines in the emission spectrum of air that did not match known elements.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/argon] Prior to 1957, the symbol for argon was "A".
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/argon] This was changed to Ar after the International Union of Pure and Applied Chemistry published the work *Nomenclature of Inorganic Chemistry* in 1957.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/argon] Argon constitutes 0.934% by volume and 1.288% by mass of Earth's atmosphere.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/argon] Air is the primary industrial source of purified argon products.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/argon] Argon is isolated from air by fractionation, most commonly by cryogenic fractional distillation, a process that also produces purified nitrogen, oxygen, neon, krypton and xenon.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/argon] Earth's crust and seawater contain 1.2 ppm and 0.45 ppm of argon, respectively.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/argon] Naturally occurring 40 K, with a half-life of 1.25×109 years, decays to stable 40 Ar (11.2%) by electron capture or positron emission, and also to stable 40 Ca (88.8%) by beta decay.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/argon] These properties and ratios are used to determine the age of rocks by K–Ar dating.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/argon] In Earth's atmosphere, 39 Ar is made by cosmic ray activity, primarily by neutron capture of 40 Ar followed by two-neutron emission.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/argon] In the subsurface environment, it is also produced through neutron capture by 39 K, followed by proton emission.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/argon] 37 Ar is created from the neutron capture by 40 Ca followed by an alpha particle emission as a result of subsurface nuclear explosions.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/argon] Between locations in the Solar System, the isotopic composition of argon varies greatly.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/argon] Where the major source of argon is the decay of 40 K in rocks, 40 Ar will be the dominant isotope, as it is on Earth.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/argon] Argon produced directly by stellar nucleosynthesis is dominated by the alpha-process nuclide 36 Ar.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/argon] Correspondingly, solar argon contains 84.6% 36 Ar (according to solar wind measurements), and the ratio of the three isotopes 36Ar : 38Ar : 40Ar in the atmospheres of the outer planets is 8400 : 1600 : 1.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/argon] This contrasts with the low abundance of primordial 36 Ar in Earth's atmosphere, which is only 31.5 ppmv (= 9340 ppmv × 0.337%), comparable with that of neon (18.18 ppmv) on Earth and with interplanetary gasses, measured by probes.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/argon] The atmospheres of Mars, Mercury and Titan (the largest moon of Saturn) contain argon, predominantly as 40 Ar.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/argon] The predominance of radiogenic 40 Ar is the reason the standard atomic weight of terrestrial argon is greater than that of the next element, potassium, a fact that was puzzling when argon was discovered.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/argon] Mendeleev positioned the elements on his periodic table in order of atomic weight, but the inertness of argon suggested a placement *before* the reactive alkali metal.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/argon] Henry Moseley later solved this problem by showing that the periodic table is actually arranged in order of atomic number (see History of the periodic table).
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/argon] Argon's complete octet of electrons indicates full s and p subshells.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/argon] This full valence shell makes argon very stable and extremely resistant to bonding with other elements.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/argon] Before 1962, argon and the other noble gases were considered to be chemically inert and unable to form compounds; however, compounds of the heavier noble gases have since been synthesized.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/argon] The first argon compound with tungsten pentacarbonyl, W(CO)5Ar, was isolated in 1975.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/argon] However, it was not widely recognised at that time.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/argon] In August 2000, another argon compound, argon fluorohydride (HArF), was formed by researchers at the University of Helsinki, by shining ultraviolet light onto frozen argon containing a small amount of hydrogen fluoride with caesium iodide.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/argon] This discovery caused the recognition that argon could form weakly bound compounds, even though it was not the first.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/argon] It is stable up to 17 kelvins (−256 °C).
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/argon] The metastable ArCF2+ 2 dication, which is valence-isoelectronic with carbonyl fluoride and phosgene, was observed in 2010.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/argon] Argon-36, in the form of argon hydride (argonium) ions, has been detected in interstellar medium associated with the Crab Nebula supernova; this was the first noble-gas molecule detected in outer space.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/argon] Solid argon hydride (Ar(H2)2) has the same crystal structure as the MgZn2 Laves phase.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/argon] It forms at pressures between 4.3 and 220 GPa, though Raman measurements suggest that the H2 molecules in Ar(H2)2 dissociate above 175 GPa.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/argon] Argon is extracted industrially by the fractional distillation of liquid air in a cryogenic air separation unit; a process that separates liquid nitrogen, which boils at 77.3 K, from argon, which boils at 87.3 K, and liquid oxygen, which boils at 90.2 K.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/argon] About 700,000 tonnes of argon are produced worldwide every year.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/argon] Other noble gases would be equally suitable for most of these applications, but argon is by far the cheapest.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/argon] It is inexpensive, since it occurs naturally in air and is readily obtained as a byproduct of cryogenic air separation in the production of liquid oxygen and liquid nitrogen: the primary constituents of air are used on a large industrial scale.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/argon] The other noble gases (except helium) are produced this way as well, but argon is the most plentiful by far.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/argon] The bulk of its applications arise simply because it is inert and relatively cheap.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/argon] Argon is used in some high-temperature industrial processes where ordinarily non-reactive substances become reactive.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/argon] For example, an argon atmosphere is used in graphite electric furnaces to prevent the graphite from burning.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/argon] For some of these processes, the presence of nitrogen or oxygen gases might cause defects within the material.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/argon] Argon is used in some types of arc welding such as gas metal arc welding and gas tungsten arc welding, as well as in the processing of titanium and other reactive elements.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/argon] An argon atmosphere is also used for growing crystals of silicon and germanium.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/argon] Argon is used in the poultry industry to asphyxiate birds, either for mass culling following disease outbreaks, or as a means of slaughter more humane than electric stunning.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/argon] Argon is denser than air and displaces oxygen close to the ground during inert gas asphyxiation.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/argon] Its non-reactive nature makes it suitable in a food product, and since it replaces oxygen within the dead bird, argon also enhances shelf life.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/argon] Argon is sometimes used for extinguishing fires where valuable equipment may be damaged by water or foam.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/argon] Liquid argon is used as the target for neutrino experiments and direct dark matter searches.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/argon] The interaction between the hypothetical WIMPs and an argon nucleus produces scintillation light that is detected by photomultiplier tubes.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/argon] Two-phase detectors containing argon gas are used to detect the ionized electrons produced during the WIMP–nucleus scattering.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/argon] As with most other liquefied noble gases, argon has a high scintillation light yield (about 51 photons/keV), is transparent to its own scintillation light, and is relatively easy to purify.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/argon] Compared to xenon, argon is cheaper and has a distinct scintillation time profile, which allows the separation of electronic recoils from nuclear recoils.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/argon] On the other hand, its intrinsic beta-ray background is larger due to 39 Ar contamination, unless one uses argon from underground sources, which has much less 39 Ar contamination.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/argon] Most of the argon in Earth's atmosphere was produced by electron capture of long-lived 40 K (40 K + e− → 40 Ar + ν) present in natural potassium within Earth.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/argon] The 39 Ar activity in the atmosphere is maintained by cosmogenic production through the knockout reaction 40 Ar(n,2n)39 Ar and similar reactions.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/argon] The half-life of 39 Ar is only 269 years.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/argon] As a result, the underground Ar, shielded by rock and water, has much less 39 Ar contamination.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/argon] Dark-matter detectors currently operating with liquid argon include DarkSide, WArP, ArDM, microCLEAN and DEAP.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/argon] Neutrino experiments include ICARUS and MicroBooNE, both of which use high-purity liquid argon in a time projection chamber for fine grained three-dimensional imaging of neutrino interactions.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/argon] At Linköping University, Sweden, the inert gas is being utilized in a vacuum chamber in which plasma is introduced to ionize metallic films.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/argon] This process results in a film usable for manufacturing computer processors.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/argon] The new process would eliminate the need for chemical baths and use of expensive, dangerous and rare materials.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/argon] Argon is used to displace oxygen- and moisture-containing air in packaging material to extend the shelf-lives of the contents (argon has the European food additive code E938).
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/argon] Aerial oxidation, hydrolysis, and other chemical reactions that degrade the products are retarded or prevented entirely.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/argon] High-purity chemicals and pharmaceuticals are sometimes packed and sealed in argon.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/argon] In winemaking, argon is used in a variety of activities to provide a barrier against oxygen at the liquid surface, which can spoil wine by fueling both microbial metabolism (as with acetic acid bacteria) and standard redox chemistry.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/argon] Argon is sometimes used as the propellant in aerosol cans.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/argon] Argon is also used as a preservative for such products as varnish, polyurethane, and paint, by displacing air to prepare a container for storage.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/argon] Since 2002, the American National Archives stores important national documents such as the Declaration of Independence and the Constitution within argon-filled cases to inhibit their degradation.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/argon] Argon is preferable to the helium that had been used in the preceding five decades, because helium gas escapes through the intermolecular pores in most containers and must be regularly replaced.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/argon] Argon may be used as the inert gas within Schlenk lines and gloveboxes.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/argon] Argon is preferred to less expensive nitrogen in cases where nitrogen may react with the reagents or apparatus.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/argon] Argon may be used as the carrier gas in gas chromatography and in electrospray ionization mass spectrometry; it is the gas of choice for the plasma used in ICP spectroscopy.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/argon] Argon is preferred for the sputter coating of specimens for scanning electron microscopy.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/argon] Argon gas is also commonly used for sputter deposition of thin films as in microelectronics and for wafer cleaning in microfabrication.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/argon] Cryosurgery procedures such as cryoablation use liquid argon to destroy tissue such as cancer cells.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/argon] It is used in a procedure called "argon-enhanced coagulation", a form of argon plasma beam electrosurgery.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/argon] The procedure carries a risk of producing gas embolism and has resulted in the death of at least one patient.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/argon] Blue argon lasers are used in surgery to weld arteries, destroy tumors, and correct eye defects.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/argon] Argon has also been used experimentally to replace nitrogen in the breathing or decompression mix known as Argox, to speed the elimination of dissolved nitrogen from the blood.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/argon] Incandescent lights are filled with argon, to preserve the filaments at high temperature from oxidation.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/argon] It is used for the specific way it ionizes and emits light, such as in plasma globes and calorimetry in experimental particle physics.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/argon] Gas-discharge lamps filled with pure argon provide lilac/violet light; with argon and some mercury, blue light.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/argon] Argon is also used for blue and green argon-ion lasers.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/argon] Argon is used for thermal insulation in energy-efficient windows.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/argon] Argon is also used in technical scuba diving to inflate a dry suit because it is inert and has low thermal conductivity.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/argon] Argon is used as a propellant in the development of the Variable Specific Impulse Magnetoplasma Rocket (VASIMR).
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/argon] Compressed argon gas is allowed to expand, to cool the seeker heads of some versions of the AIM-9 Sidewinder missile and other missiles that use cooled thermal seeker heads.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/argon] Argon-39, with a half-life of 269 years, has been used for a number of applications, primarily ice core and ground water dating.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/argon] Also, potassium–argon dating and related argon-argon dating are used to date sedimentary, metamorphic, and igneous rocks.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/argon] Argon has been used by athletes as a doping agent to simulate hypoxic conditions.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/argon] In 2014, the World Anti-Doping Agency (WADA) added argon and xenon to the list of prohibited substances and methods, although at this time there is no reliable test for abuse.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/argon] Although argon is non-toxic, it is 38% more dense than air and therefore considered a dangerous asphyxiant in closed areas.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/argon] It is difficult to detect because it is colorless, odorless, and tasteless.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/argon] A 1994 incident, in which a man was asphyxiated after entering an argon-filled section of oil pipe under construction in Alaska, highlights the dangers of argon tank leakage in confined spaces and emphasizes the need for proper use, storage and handling.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/arthur-b-guise-medal] Guise Medal** was established in 1983 and has been awarded annually starting in 1985 by the Society of Fire Protection Engineers.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/arthur-b-guise-medal] Named in memory of Arthur Guise, an engineer who developed dry chemicals as fire extinguishing agents, it recognizes eminent achievement in the advancement of the science and technology of fire protection engineering.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/automatic-fire-suppression] Today there are numerous types of automatic fire suppression systems and standards for each one.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/automatic-fire-suppression] Systems are as diverse as the many applications.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/automatic-fire-suppression] In general, however, automatic fire suppression systems fall into two categories: *engineered* and *pre-engineered* systems.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/automatic-fire-suppression] By definition, an automatic fire suppression system can operate without human intervention.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/automatic-fire-suppression] To do so it must possess a means of detection, actuation and delivery.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/automatic-fire-suppression] In many systems, detection is accomplished by mechanical or electrical means.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/automatic-fire-suppression] Mechanical detection uses fusible-link or thermo-bulb detectors.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/automatic-fire-suppression] These detectors are designed to separate at a specific temperature and release tension on a release mechanism.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/automatic-fire-suppression] Electrical detection uses heat detectors equipped with self-restoring, normally-open contacts which close when a predetermined temperature is reached.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/automatic-fire-suppression] Remote and local manual operation is also possible.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/automatic-fire-suppression] Actuation usually involves either a pressurized fluid and a release valve, or in some cases an electric pump.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/automatic-fire-suppression] Delivery is accomplished by means of piping and nozzles.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/automatic-fire-suppression] Nozzle design is specific to the agent used and coverage desired.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/automatic-fire-suppression] Water is the most prevalent fire suppression agent in use worldwide.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/automatic-fire-suppression] However, the use of water does have some limitations, which can range from inadequate supplies (particularly in less developed regions) to operations and processes which are highly susceptible to water damage.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/automatic-fire-suppression] In some cases, certain contents or processes (such as water-reactive chemicals or metals, molten materials, etc.) are truly incompatible with water; water discharge could lead to explosion.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/automatic-fire-suppression] Despite their effectiveness, chemical fire extinguishing agents are not without disadvantages.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/automatic-fire-suppression] In the early 20th century, carbon tetrachloride was extensively used as a dry cleaning solvent, a refrigerant and as a fire extinguishing agent.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/automatic-fire-suppression] In time, it was found carbon tetrachloride could lead to severe health effects.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/automatic-fire-suppression] From the mid-1960s Halon 1301 was the industry standard for protecting high-value assets from the threat of fire.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/automatic-fire-suppression] Halon 1301 had many benefits as a fire suppression agent; it is fast-acting, safe for assets and required minimal storage space.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/automatic-fire-suppression] Halon 1301's major drawbacks are that it depletes atmospheric ozone and is potentially harmful to humans.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/automatic-fire-suppression] Since 1987, some 191 nations have signed The Montreal Protocol on Substances That Deplete the Ozone Layer.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/automatic-fire-suppression] The Protocol is an international treaty designed to protect the ozone layer by phasing out the production of a number of substances believed to be responsible for ozone depletion.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/automatic-fire-suppression] Among these were halogenated hydrocarbons often used in fire suppression.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/automatic-fire-suppression] As a result, manufacturers have focused on alternatives to Halon 1301 and Halon 1211 (halogenated hydrocarbons).
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/automatic-fire-suppression] A number of countries have also taken steps to mandate the removal of installed Halon systems.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/automatic-fire-suppression] Most notably these include Germany and Australia, the first two countries in the world to require this action.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/automatic-fire-suppression] In both of these countries complete removal of installed Halon systems has been completed except for a very few essential-use applications.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/automatic-fire-suppression] The European Union is currently undergoing a similar mandated removal of installed Halon systems.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/automatic-fire-suppression] The first fire extinguisher patent was issued to Alanson Crane of Virginia on Feb.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/automatic-fire-suppression] The first fire sprinkler system was patented by H.W.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/automatic-fire-suppression] But the first practical automatic sprinkler system was invented in 1874 by Henry S.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/automatic-fire-suppression] He installed the system in a piano factory he owned.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/automatic-fire-suppression] Since the early 1990s manufacturers have successfully developed safe and effective Halon alternatives.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/automatic-fire-suppression] These include DuPont's FM-200, American Pacific's Halotron, FirePro's FPC Compound, Plumis’ Automist and 3M's Novec 1230 Fire Protection Fluid.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/automatic-fire-suppression] Generally, the Halon replacement agents available today fall into two broad categories, in-kind (gaseous extinguishing agents) or not in-kind (alternative technologies).
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/automatic-fire-suppression] In-kind gaseous agents generally fall into two further categories, halocarbons and inert gases.
[src:automatic-fire-suppression/automatic-fire-suppression] Not in-kind alternatives include such options as water mist or the use of early warning smoke detection systems.
